# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: experimental-design
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] In the statistical theory of the design of experiments, **blocking** is the arranging of experimental units that are similar to one another in groups (blocks) based on one or more variables.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] These variables are chosen carefully to minimize the effect of their variability on the observed outcomes.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] There are different ways that blocking can be implemented, resulting in different confounding effects.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] However, the different methods share the same purpose: to control variability introduced by specific factors that could influence the outcome of an experiment.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] The roots of blocking originated from the statistician, Ronald Fisher, following his development of ANOVA.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] The use of blocking in experimental design has an evolving history that spans multiple disciplines.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] The foundational concepts of blocking date back to the early 20th century with statisticians like Ronald A.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] His work in developing analysis of variance (ANOVA) set the groundwork for grouping experimental units to control for extraneous variables.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] Blocking evolved over the years, leading to the formalization of randomized block designs and Latin square designs.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] Today, blocking still plays a pivotal role in experimental design, and in recent years, advancements in statistical software and computational capabilities have allowed researchers to explore more intricate blocking designs.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] We often want to reduce or eliminate the influence of some confounding factor when designing an experiment.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] We can sometimes do this by "blocking", which involves the separate consideration of blocks of data that have different levels of exposure to that factor.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] In the examples listed above, a nuisance variable is a variable that is not the primary focus of the study but can affect the outcomes of the experiment.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] They are considered potential sources of variability that, if not controlled or accounted for, may confound the interpretation between the independent and dependent variables.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] To address nuisance variables, researchers can employ different methods such as blocking or randomization.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] Blocking involves grouping experimental units based on levels of the nuisance variable to control for its influence.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] Randomization helps distribute the effects of nuisance variables evenly across treatment groups.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] By using one of these methods to account for nuisance variables, researchers can enhance the internal validity of their experiments, ensuring that the effects observed are more likely attributable to the manipulated variables rather than extraneous influences.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] In the first example provided above, the sex of the patient would be a nuisance variable.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] For example, consider if the drug was a diet pill and the researchers wanted to test the effect of the diet pills on weight loss.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] The explanatory variable is the diet pill and the response variable is the amount of weight loss.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] Although the sex of the patient is not the main focus of the experiment—the effect of the drug is—it is possible that the sex of the individual will affect the amount of weight lost.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] In the statistical theory of the design of experiments, blocking is the arranging of experimental units in groups (blocks) that are similar to one another.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] Typically, a blocking factor is a source of variability that is not of primary interest to the experimenter.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] When studying probability theory the blocks method consists of splitting a sample into blocks (groups) separated by smaller subblocks so that the blocks can be considered almost independent.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] The blocks method helps proving limit theorems in the case of dependent random variables.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] Bernstein: The method was successfully applied in the theory of sums of dependent random variables and in extreme value theory.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] In our previous diet pills example, a blocking factor could be the sex of a patient.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] We could put individuals into one of two blocks (male or female).
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] And within each of the two blocks, we can randomly assign the patients to either the diet pill (treatment) or placebo pill (control).
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] By blocking on sex, this source of variability is controlled, therefore, leading to greater interpretation of how the diet pills affect weight loss.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] A nuisance factor is used as a blocking factor if every level of the primary factor occurs the same number of times with each level of the nuisance factor.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] The analysis of the experiment will focus on the effect of varying levels of the primary factor within each block of the experiment.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] Blocking is used to remove the effects of a few of the most important nuisance variables.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] Randomization is then used to reduce the contaminating effects of the remaining nuisance variables.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] For important nuisance variables, blocking will yield higher significance in the variables of interest than randomizing.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] Implementing blocking in experimental design involves a series of steps to effectively control for extraneous variables and enhance the precision of treatment effect estimates.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] Identify potential factors that are not the primary focus of the study but could introduce variability.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] Carefully choose blocking factors based on their relevance to the study as well as their potential to confound the primary factors of interest.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] There are consequences to partitioning a certain sized experiment into a certain number of blocks as the number of blocks determines the number of confounded effects.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] You may choose to randomly assign experimental units to treatment conditions within each block which may help ensure that any unaccounted for variability is spread evenly across treatment groups.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] However, depending on how you assign treatments to blocks, you may obtain a different number of confounded effects.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] Therefore, the number of as well as which specific effects get confounded can be chosen which means that assigning treatments to blocks is superior over random assignment.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] By running a different design for each replicate, where a different effect gets confounded each time, the interaction effects are partially confounded instead of completely sacrificing one single effect.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] Replication enhances the reliability of results and allows for a more robust assessment of treatment effects.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] One useful way to look at a randomized block experiment is to consider it as a collection of completely randomized experiments, each run within one of the blocks of the total experiment.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] Suppose engineers at a semiconductor manufacturing facility want to test whether different wafer implant material dosages have a significant effect on resistivity measurements after a diffusion process taking place in a furnace.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] They have four different dosages they want to try and enough experimental wafers from the same lot to run three wafers at each of the dosages.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] The nuisance factor they are concerned with is "furnace run" since it is known that each furnace run differs from the last and impacts many process parameters.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] An ideal way to run this experiment would be to run all the 4x3=12 wafers in the same furnace run.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] That would eliminate the nuisance furnace factor completely.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] However, regular production wafers have furnace priority, and only a few experimental wafers are allowed into any furnace run at the same time.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] A non-blocked way to run this experiment would be to run each of the twelve experimental wafers, in random order, one per furnace run.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] That would increase the experimental error of each resistivity measurement by the run-to-run furnace variability and make it more difficult to study the effects of the different dosages.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] The blocked way to run this experiment, assuming you can convince manufacturing to let you put four experimental wafers in a furnace run, would be to put four wafers with different dosages in each of three furnace runs.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] The only randomization would be choosing which of the three wafers with dosage 1 would go into furnace run 1, and similarly for the wafers with dosages 2, 3 and 4.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] Let *X*1 be dosage "level" and *X*2 be the blocking factor furnace run.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] An alternate way of summarizing the design trials would be to use a 4x3 matrix whose 4 rows are the levels of the treatment *X*1 and whose columns are the 3 levels of the blocking variable *X*2.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] The cells in the matrix have indices that match the *X*1, *X*2 combinations above.
[src:experimental-design/blocking-statistics] By extension, note that the trials for any K-factor randomized block design are simply the cell indices of a *k* dimensional matrix.
[src:experimental-design/completely-randomized-design] In the design of experiments, **completely randomized designs** are for studying the effects of one primary factor without the need to take other nuisance variables into account.
[src:experimental-design/completely-randomized-design] This article describes completely randomized designs that have one primary factor.
[src:experimental-design/completely-randomized-design] The experiment compares the values of a response variable based on the different levels of that primary factor.
[src:experimental-design/completely-randomized-design] For completely randomized designs, the levels of the primary factor are randomly assigned to the experimental units.
[src:experimental-design/completely-randomized-design] To randomize is to determine the run sequence of the experimental units randomly.
[src:experimental-design/completely-randomized-design] For example, if there are 3 levels of the primary factor with each level to be run 2 times, then there are 6!
[src:experimental-design/completely-randomized-design] (where ! denotes factorial) possible run sequences (or ways to order the experimental trials).
[src:experimental-design/completely-randomized-design] Because of the replication, the number of unique orderings is 90 (since 90 = 6!/(2!*2!*2!)).
[src:experimental-design/completely-randomized-design] An example of an unrandomized design would be to always run 2 replications for the first level, then 2 for the second level, and finally 2 for the third level.
[src:experimental-design/completely-randomized-design] To randomize the runs, one way would be to put 6 slips of paper in a box with 2 having level 1, 2 having level 2, and 2 having level 3.
[src:experimental-design/completely-randomized-design] Before each run, one of the slips would be drawn blindly from the box and the level selected would be used for the next run of the experiment.
[src:experimental-design/completely-randomized-design] In practice, the randomization is typically performed by a computer program.
[src:experimental-design/completely-randomized-design] However, the randomization can also be generated from random number tables or by some physical mechanism (e.g., drawing the slips of paper).
[src:experimental-design/completely-randomized-design] and the total sample size (number of runs) is *N* = *k* × *L* × *n*.
[src:experimental-design/completely-randomized-design] Balance dictates that the number of replications be the same at each level of the factor (this will maximize the sensitivity of subsequent statistical *t*- (or *F*-) tests).
[src:experimental-design/completely-randomized-design] Note that in this example there are 12!/(3!*3!*3!*3!) = 369,600 ways to run the experiment, all equally likely to be picked by a randomization procedure.
[src:experimental-design/completely-randomized-design] Statistical tests for levels of *X*1 are those used for a one-way ANOVA and are detailed in the article on analysis of variance.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] The **design of experiments** (**DOE**), also known as **experimental design**, refers to the construction of procedures that attempt to explain how changes in one aspect of a system will lead to changes in other aspects of a system.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] In general, the design of experiments involves decisions about which aspects of the system to change and which to control based on hypotheses about the sources of variance in the aspects of the system considered by the experimenter.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] DOE is generally associated with experiments where the design introduces conditions that directly affect the variation, but DOE may also refer to the design of quasi-experiments, in which natural conditions that influence the variation are selected for observation.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Experimental design involves not only the selection of suitable independent, dependent, and control variables, but planning the delivery of the experiment under statistically optimal conditions given the constraints of available resources.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] There are multiple approaches for determining the set of design points (unique combinations of the settings of the independent variables) to be used in the experiment.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Main concerns in experimental design include the establishment of validity, reliability, and replicability.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] For example, these concerns can be partially addressed by carefully choosing the independent variable, reducing the risk of measurement error, and ensuring that the documentation of the method is sufficiently detailed.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Related concerns include achieving appropriate levels of statistical power and sensitivity.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Correctly designed experiments advance knowledge in the natural and social sciences and engineering, with design of experiments methodology recognised as a key tool in the successful implementation of a Quality by Design (QbD) framework.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Other applications include marketing and policy making.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] The study of the design of experiments is an important topic in metascience.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] A theory of statistical inference was developed by Charles S.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Peirce in "Illustrations of the Logic of Science" (1877–1878) and "A Theory of Probable Inference" (1883), two publications that emphasized the importance of randomization-based inference in statistics.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Peirce randomly assigned volunteers to a blinded, repeated-measures design to evaluate their ability to discriminate weights.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Peirce's experiment inspired other researchers in psychology and education, which developed a research tradition of randomized experiments in laboratories and specialized textbooks in the 1800s.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Peirce also contributed the first English-language publication on an optimal design for regression models in 1876.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] A pioneering optimal design for polynomial regression was suggested by Gergonne in 1815.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] In 1918, Kirstine Smith published optimal designs for polynomials of degree six (and less).
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Herman Chernoff wrote an overview of optimal sequential designs, while adaptive designs have been surveyed by S.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] One specific type of sequential design is the "two-armed bandit", generalized to the multi-armed bandit, on which early work was done by Herbert Robbins in 1952.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] A methodology for designing experiments was proposed by Ronald Fisher, in his innovative books: *The Arrangement of Field Experiments* (1926) and *The Design of Experiments* (1935).
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Much of his pioneering work dealt with agricultural applications of statistical methods.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] As a mundane example, he described how to test the lady tasting tea hypothesis, that a certain lady could distinguish by flavour alone whether the milk or the tea was first placed in the cup.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] These methods have been broadly adapted in biological, psychological, and agricultural research.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] or traditional treatment that acts as baseline.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Random assignment is the process of assigning individuals at random to groups or to different groups in an experiment, so that each individual of the population has the same chance of becoming a participant in the study.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] The random assignment of individuals to groups (or conditions within a group) distinguishes a rigorous, "true" experiment from an observational study or "quasi-experiment".
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] There is an extensive body of mathematical theory that explores the consequences of making the allocation of units to treatments by means of some random mechanism (such as tables of random numbers, or the use of randomization devices such as playing cards or dice).
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] , which makes effects due to factors other than the treatment to appear to result from the treatment.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] The risks associated with random allocation (such as having a serious imbalance in a key characteristic between a treatment group and a control group) are calculable and hence can be managed down to an acceptable level by using enough experimental units.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] However, if the population is divided into several subpopulations that somehow differ, and the research requires each subpopulation to be equal in size, stratified sampling can be used.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] In that way, the units in each subpopulation are randomized, but not the whole sample.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] from the larger population; the probable error of such an extrapolation depends on the sample size, among other things.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] ; thus they are repeated and full experiments are replicated to help identify the sources of variation, to better estimate the true effects of treatments, to further strengthen the experiment's reliability and validity, and to add to the existing knowledge of the topic.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Blocking is the non-random arrangement of experimental units into groups (blocks) consisting of units that are similar to one another.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Blocking reduces known but irrelevant sources of variation between units and thus allows greater precision in the estimation of the source of variation under study.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Orthogonality concerns the forms of comparison (contrasts) that can be legitimately and efficiently carried out.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Contrasts can be represented by vectors and sets of orthogonal contrasts are uncorrelated and independently distributed if the data are normal.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Because of this independence, each orthogonal treatment provides different information to the others.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] − 1 orthogonal contrasts, all the information that can be captured from the experiment is obtainable from the set of contrasts.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] of several factors (independent variables).
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] , a collection of models that partition the observed variance into components, according to what factors the experiment must estimate or test.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] This example of design experiments is attributed to Harold Hotelling, building on examples from Frank Yates.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] The experiments designed in this example involve combinatorial designs.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Weights of eight objects are measured using a pan balance and set of standard weights.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Each weighing measures the weight difference between objects in the left pan and any objects in the right pan by adding calibrated weights to the lighter pan until the balance is in equilibrium.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Each measurement has a random error $\epsilon$ .
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] The average error is zero; the standard deviations of the probability distribution of the errors is the same number σ on different weighings; errors on different weighings are independent.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Let *y**i* be the measured difference for *i* = 1, ..., 8.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] The first design is represented by an identity matrix while the second design is represented by an 8x8 Hadamard matrix, H , both examples of weighing matrices.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] The weights are typically estimated using the method of least squares.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] The question of design of experiments is: *which experiment is better*?
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] A similar result follows for the remaining weight estimates.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Thus, the second experiment gives us 8 times as much precision for the estimate of a single item, despite costing the same number of resources (number of weightings).
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Many problems of the design of experiments involve combinatorial designs, as in this example and others.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] False positive conclusions, often resulting from the pressure to publish or the author's own confirmation bias, are an inherent hazard in many fields.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Use of double-blind designs can prevent biases potentially leading to false positives in the data collection phase.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] When a double-blind design is used, participants are randomly assigned to experimental groups but the researcher is unaware of what participants belong to which group.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Therefore, the researcher can not affect the participants' response to the intervention.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Experimental designs with undisclosed degrees of freedom are a problem, in that they can lead to conscious or unconscious "p-hacking": trying multiple things until you get the desired result.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] It typically involves the manipulation – perhaps unconsciously – of the process of statistical analysis and the degrees of freedom until they return a figure below the p<.05 level of statistical significance.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] P-hacking can be prevented by preregistering researches, in which researchers have to send their data analysis plan to the journal they wish to publish their paper in before they even start their data collection, so no data manipulation is possible.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Clear and complete documentation of the experimental methodology is also important in order to support replication of results.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] An experimental design or randomized clinical trial requires careful consideration of several factors before actually doing the experiment.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] An experimental design is the laying out of a detailed experimental plan in advance of doing the experiment.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Are control conditions needed, and what should they be?
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Manipulation checks: did the manipulation really work?
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] How many units must be collected for the experiment to be generalisable and have enough power?
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] What is the relevance of interactions between factors?
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] What is the influence of delayed effects of substantive factors on outcomes?
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] How do response shifts affect self-report measures?
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] How feasible is repeated administration of the same measurement instruments to the same units at different occasions, with a post-test and follow-up tests?
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Should the client/patient, researcher or even the analyst of the data be blind to conditions?
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] What is the feasibility of subsequent application of different conditions to the same units?
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] How many of each control and noise factors should be taken into account?
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] The independent variable of a study often has many levels or different groups.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] In a true experiment, researchers can have an experimental group, which is where their intervention testing the hypothesis is implemented, and a control group, which has all the same element as the experimental group, without the interventional element.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Thus, when everything else except for one intervention is held constant, researchers can certify with some certainty that this one element is what caused the observed change.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] In some instances, having a control group is not ethical.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] This is sometimes solved using two different experimental groups.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] In some cases, independent variables cannot be manipulated, for example when testing the difference between two groups who have a different disease, or testing the difference between genders (obviously variables that would be hard or unethical to assign participants to).
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] In these cases, a quasi-experimental design may be used.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] In the pure experimental design, the independent (predictor) variable is manipulated by the researcher – that is – every participant of the research is chosen randomly from the population, and each participant chosen is assigned randomly to conditions of the independent variable.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Only when this is done is it possible to certify with high probability that the reason for the differences in the outcome variables are caused by the different conditions.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Therefore, researchers should choose the experimental design over other design types whenever possible.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] However, the nature of the independent variable does not always allow for manipulation.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] In those cases, researchers must be aware of not certifying about causal attribution when their design doesn't allow for it.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] The same goes for studies with correlational design.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] It is best that a process be in reasonable statistical control prior to conducting designed experiments.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] When this is not possible, proper blocking, replication, and randomization allow for the careful conduct of designed experiments.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] To control for nuisance variables, researchers institute **control checks** as additional measures.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Investigators should ensure that uncontrolled influences (e.g., source credibility perception) do not skew the findings of the study.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] A manipulation check is one example of a control check.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Manipulation checks allow investigators to isolate the chief variables to strengthen support that these variables are operating as planned.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] One of the most important requirements of experimental research designs is the necessity of eliminating the effects of spurious, intervening, and antecedent variables.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] In the most basic model, cause (X) leads to effect (Y).
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] But there could be a third variable (Z) that influences (Y), and X might not be the true cause at all.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Z is said to be a spurious variable and must be controlled for.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] The same is true for intervening variables (a variable in between the supposed cause (X) and the effect (Y)), and anteceding variables (a variable prior to the supposed cause (X) that is the true cause).
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] When a third variable is involved and has not been controlled for, the relation is said to be a zero order relationship.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] In most practical applications of experimental research designs there are several causes (X1, X2, X3).
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] In most designs, only one of these causes is manipulated at a time.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Some efficient designs for estimating several main effects were found independently and in near succession by Raj Chandra Bose and K.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Kishen in 1940 at the Indian Statistical Institute, but remained little known until the Plackett–Burman designs were published in *Biometrika* in 1946.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Rao introduced the concepts of orthogonal arrays as experimental designs.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] This concept played a central role in the development of Taguchi methods by Genichi Taguchi, which took place during his visit to Indian Statistical Institute in early 1950s.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] His methods were successfully applied and adopted by Japanese and Indian industries and subsequently were also embraced by US industry albeit with some reservations.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] In 1950, Gertrude Mary Cox and William Gemmell Cochran published the book *Experimental Designs,* which became the major reference work on the design of experiments for statisticians for years afterwards.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Developments of the theory of linear models have encompassed and surpassed the cases that concerned early writers.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Today, the theory rests on advanced topics in linear algebra, algebra and combinatorics.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Some important contributors to the field of experimental designs are C.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Nelder, Andrej Pázman, Friedrich Pukelsheim, D.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Hunter have reached generations of students and practitioners.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Furthermore, there is ongoing discussion of experimental design in the context of model building for models either static or dynamic models, also known as system identification.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Laws and ethical considerations preclude some carefully designed experiments with human subjects.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Legal constraints are dependent on jurisdiction.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Constraints may involve institutional review boards, informed consent and confidentiality affecting both clinical (medical) trials and behavioral and social science experiments.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] In the field of toxicology, for example, experimentation is performed on laboratory *animals* with the goal of defining safe exposure limits for *humans*.
[src:experimental-design/design-of-experiments] Balancing the constraints are views from the medical field.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] In combinatorics and in experimental design, a **Latin square** is an *n* × *n* array filled with *n* different symbols, each occurring exactly once in each row and exactly once in each column.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] The name "Latin square" was inspired by mathematical papers by Leonhard Euler (1707–1783), who used Latin characters as symbols, but any set of symbols can be used: in the above example, the alphabetic sequence A, B, C can be replaced by the integer sequence 1, 2, 3.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Euler began the general theory of Latin squares.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] The Korean mathematician Choi Seok-jeong was the first to publish an example of Latin squares of order nine, in order to construct a magic square in 1700, predating Leonhard Euler by 67 years.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] This account follows McKay, Meynert & Myrvold (2007, p.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] The counting of Latin squares has a long history, but the published accounts contain many errors.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Euler in 1782, and Cayley in 1890, both knew the number of reduced Latin squares up to order five.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] In 1915, MacMahon approached the problem in a different way, but initially obtained the wrong value for order five.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] M.Frolov in 1890, and Tarry in 1901, found the number of reduced squares of order six.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Frolov gave an incorrect count of reduced squares of order seven.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Schönhardt, gave the number of isotopy classes of orders up to six.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Norton found 562 isotopy classes of order seven, but acknowledged that his method was incomplete.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Sade, in 1951, but privately published earlier in 1948, and P.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Saxena found more classes and, in 1966, D.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Preece noted that this corrected Norton's result to 564 isotopy classes.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Brown announced an incorrect value of 563, which has often been repeated.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] He also gave the wrong number of isotopy classes of order eight.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] The correct number of reduced squares of order eight had already been found by M.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Wells in 1967, and the numbers of isotopy classes, in 1990, by G.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] The number of reduced squares for order nine was obtained by S.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] A Latin square is said to be *reduced* (also, *normalized* or *in standard form*) if both its first row and its first column are in their natural order.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] For example, the Latin square above is not reduced because its first column is A, C, B rather than A, B, C.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Any Latin square can be reduced by permuting (that is, reordering) the rows and columns.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] This Latin square is reduced; both its first row and its first column are alphabetically ordered A, B, C.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] If each entry of an *n* × *n* Latin square is written as a triple (*r*,*c*,*s*), where *r* is the row, *c* is the column, and *s* is the symbol, we obtain a set of *n*2 triples called the orthogonal array representation of the square.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] where for example the triple (2, 3, 1) means that in row 2 and column 3 there is the symbol 1.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] This means that the *n*2 ordered pairs (*r*, *c*) are all the pairs (*i*, *j*) with 1 ≤ *i*, *j* ≤ *n*, once each.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] The same is true of the ordered pairs (*r*, *s*) and the ordered pairs (*c*, *s*).
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] The orthogonal array representation shows that rows, columns and symbols play rather similar roles, as will be made clear below.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Many operations on a Latin square produce another Latin square (for example, turning it upside down).
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] If we permute the rows, permute the columns, or permute the names of the symbols of a Latin square, we obtain a new Latin square said to be *isotopic* to the first.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Isotopism is an equivalence relation, so the set of all Latin squares is divided into subsets, called *isotopy classes*, such that two squares in the same class are isotopic and two squares in different classes are not isotopic.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Two Latin squares *L*1 and *L*2 of side n with common symbol set S that is also the index set for the rows and columns of each square are *isomorphic* if there is a bijection *g*: *S* → *S* such that *g*(*L*1(*i*, *j*)) = *L*2(*g*(*i*), *g*(*j*)) for all i, j in S.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] An alternate way to define isomorphic Latin squares is to say that a pair of isotopic Latin squares are isomorphic if the three bijections used to show that they are isotopic are, in fact, equal.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Isomorphism is also an equivalence relation and its equivalence classes are called *isomorphism classes*.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Another type of operation is easiest to explain using the orthogonal array representation of the Latin square.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] If we systematically and consistently reorder the three items in each triple (that is, permute the three columns in the array form), another orthogonal array (and, thus, another Latin square) is obtained.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] For example, we can replace each triple (*r*,*c*,*s*) by (*c*,*r*,*s*) which corresponds to transposing the square (reflecting about its main diagonal), or we could replace each triple (*r*,*c*,*s*) by (*c*,*s*,*r*), which is a more complicated operation.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Altogether there are 6 possibilities including "do nothing", giving us 6 Latin squares called the conjugates (also parastrophes) of the original square.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Finally, we can combine these two equivalence operations: two Latin squares are said to be *paratopic*, also *main class isotopic*, if one of them is isotopic to a conjugate of the other.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] This is again an equivalence relation, with the equivalence classes called *main classes*, *species*, or *paratopy classes*.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Each main class contains up to six isotopy classes.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] There is no known easily computable formula for the number *Ln* of *n* × *n* Latin squares with symbols 1, 2, ..., *n*.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] The most accurate upper and lower bounds known for large n are far apart.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] A simple and explicit formula for the number of Latin squares was published in 1992, but it is still not easily computable due to the exponential increase in the number of terms.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] The table below contains all known exact values.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] It can be seen that the numbers grow exceedingly quickly.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] For each n, the number of Latin squares altogether (sequence A002860 in the OEIS) is *n*!
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] (*n* − 1)! times the number of reduced Latin squares (sequence A000315 in the OEIS).
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] For each n, each isotopy class (sequence A040082 in the OEIS) contains up to (*n*!)3 Latin squares (the exact number varies), while each main class (sequence A003090 in the OEIS) contains either 1, 2, 3 or 6 isotopy classes.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] The number of structurally distinct Latin squares (i.e. the squares cannot be made identical by means of rotation, reflection, and permutation of the symbols) for n = 1 up to 7 is 1, 1, 1, 12, 192, 145164, 1524901344 respectively (sequence A264603 in the OEIS).
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] We give one example of a Latin square from each main class up to order five.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Two Latin squares of the same order *n* are called **orthogonal** if, by overlaying them, one gets every ordered pair (*a*,*b*) of symbols where *a* is a symbol in the first square and *b* is one in the second square.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Orthogonal pairs and more generally sets of pairwise orthogonal Latin squares are important in design theory and finite geometry.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] A Latin rectangle is an *m*-by-*n* rectangle, where *m* < *n*, such that each number 1, ..., *n* appears exactly once in each row and at most once in each column.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Any Latin rectangle can be completed to a Latin square by adding rows.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] More generally, one may consider the problem of whether a partial filling of an *n*-by-*n* square with numbers 1, ..., *n* that does not contain two equal entries in any row or column can be completed to a Latin square.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] If *n* − 1 or fewer filled cells are given, this is always possible.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Various other completability questions have been considered.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] The problem of determining if a partially filled square can be completed to form a Latin square is NP-complete.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] A *critical set* in a Latin square is a partial Latin square that has a unique completion, but for which no proper subset has a unique completion.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] The notations scs(*n*) and lcs(*n*) denote, respectively, the smallest and largest possible size of a critical set in any Latin square of order *n*.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] A **transversal** in a Latin square is a choice of *n* cells, where each row contains one cell, each column contains one cell, and there is one cell containing each symbol.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] One can consider a Latin square as a complete bipartite graph in which the rows are vertices of one part, the columns are vertices of the other part, each cell is an edge (between its row and its column), and the symbols are colors.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] The rules of the Latin squares imply that this is a proper edge coloring.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] With this definition, a Latin transversal is a matching in which each edge has a different color; such a matching is called a rainbow matching.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Therefore, many results on Latin squares/rectangles are contained in papers with the term "rainbow matching" in their title, and vice versa.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] For example, when *n* is even, an *n*-by-*n* Latin square in which the value of cell *i*,*j* is (*i*+*j*) mod *n* has no transversal.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Ryser conjectured that, when *n* is **odd**, every *n*-by-*n* Latin square has a transversal.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Stein and Brualdi conjectured that, when *n* is **even**, every *n*-by-*n* Latin square has a **partial** transversal of size *n*−1.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] A more general conjecture of Stein is that a transversal of size *n*−1 exists not only in Latin squares but also in any *n*-by-*n* array of *n* symbols, as long as each symbol appears exactly *n* times.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] For small squares it is possible to generate permutations and test whether the Latin square property is met.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] For larger squares, Jacobson and Matthews' algorithm allows sampling from a uniform distribution over the space of *n* × *n* Latin squares.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Sets of Latin squares that are orthogonal to each other have found an application as error correcting codes in situations where communication is disturbed by more types of noise than simple white noise, such as when attempting to transmit broadband Internet over powerlines.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Firstly, the message is sent by using several frequencies, or channels, a common method that makes the signal less vulnerable to noise at any one specific frequency.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] A letter in the message to be sent is encoded by sending a series of signals at different frequencies at successive time intervals.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] In the example below, the letters A to L are encoded by sending signals at four different frequencies, in four time slots.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] The letter C, for instance, is encoded by first sending at frequency 3, then 4, 1 and 2.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] The encoding of the twelve letters are formed from three Latin squares that are orthogonal to each other.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Now imagine that there's added noise in channels 1 and 2 during the whole transmission.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] In other words, in the first slot we receive signals from both frequency 1 and frequency 2; while the third slot has signals from frequencies 1, 2 and 3.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Because of the noise, we can no longer tell if the first two slots were 1,1 or 1,2 or 2,1 or 2,2.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] But the 1,2 case is the only one that yields a sequence matching a letter in the above table, the letter A.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Again, we are able to infer from the table of encodings that it must have been the letter A being transmitted.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] The number of errors this code can spot is one less than the number of time slots.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] It has also been proven that if the number of frequencies is a prime or a power of a prime, the orthogonal Latin squares produce error detecting codes that are as efficient as possible.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] The popular Sudoku puzzles are a special case of Latin squares; any solution to a Sudoku puzzle is a Latin square.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Sudoku imposes the additional restriction that nine particular 3 × 3 adjacent subsquares must also contain the digits 1–9 (in the standard version).
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] The more recent KenKen and Strimko puzzles are also examples of Latin squares.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Latin squares have been used as the basis for several board games, notably the popular abstract strategy game Kamisado.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Latin squares are used in the design of agronomic research experiments to minimise experimental errors.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] The Latin square also figures in the arms of the Statistical Society of Canada, being specifically mentioned in its blazon.
[src:experimental-design/latin-square] Also, it appears in the logo of the International Biometric Society.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Randomization is not haphazard; instead, a random process is a sequence of random variables describing a process whose outcomes do not follow a deterministic pattern but follow an evolution described by probability distributions.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] For example, a random sample of individuals from a population refers to a sample where every individual has a known probability of being sampled.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] This would be contrasted with nonprobability sampling, where arbitrary individuals are selected.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] A runs test can be used to determine whether the occurrence of a set of measured values is random.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Randomization is widely applied in various fields, especially in scientific research, statistical analysis, and resource allocation, to ensure fairness and validity in the outcomes.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Randomization has many uses in gambling, political use, statistical analysis, art, cryptography, gaming and other fields.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] In the world of gambling, the integrity and fairness of games hinge significantly on effective randomization.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] This principle serves as a cornerstone in gambling, ensuring that each game outcome is unpredictable and not manipulable.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] The necessity for advanced randomization methods stems from the potential for skilled gamblers to exploit weaknesses in poorly randomized systems.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] High-quality randomization thwarts attempts at prediction or manipulation, maintaining the fairness of games.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] A quintessential example of randomization in gambling is the shuffling of playing cards.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] This process must be thoroughly random to prevent any predictability in the order of cards.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Casinos often employ automatic shuffling machines, which enhance randomness beyond what manual shuffling can achieve.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] With the rise of online casinos, digital random number generators (RNGs) have become crucial.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] These RNGs use complex algorithms to produce outcomes that are as unpredictable as their real-world counterparts.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] The gambling industry invests heavily in research to develop more effective randomization techniques.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] To ensure that gambling games are fair and random, regulatory bodies rigorously test and certify shuffling and random number generation methods.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] This oversight is vital in maintaining trust in the gambling industry, ensuring that players have equal chances of winning.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] The unpredictability inherent in randomization is also a key factor in the psychological appeal of gambling.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] The thrill and suspense created by the uncertainty of outcomes contribute significantly to the allure and excitement of gambling games.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] In summary, randomization in gambling is not just a technical necessity; it is a fundamental principle that upholds the fairness, integrity, and thrill of the games.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] The concept of randomization in political systems, specifically through the method of allotment or sortition, has ancient roots and contemporary relevance, significantly impacting the evolution and practice of democracy.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] In the fifth century BC, Athenian democracy was pioneering in its approach to ensuring political equality, or isonomia.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Central to this system was the principle of random selection, seen as a cornerstone for fair representation.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] The unique structure of Greek democracy, which translates to "rule by the people," was exemplified by administrative roles being rotated among citizens, selected randomly through lot.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] This method was perceived as more democratic than elections, which the Athenians argued could lead to inequalities.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] They believed that elections, which often favored candidates based on merit or popularity, contradicted the principle of equal rights for all citizens.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Furthermore, the random allotment of positions like magistrates or jury members served as a deterrent to vote-buying and corruption, as it was impossible to predict who would be chosen for these roles.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] In modern times, the concept of allotment, also known as sortition, is primarily seen in the selection of jurors within Anglo-Saxon legal systems, such as those in the UK and the United States.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] However, its political implications extend further.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] There have been various proposals to integrate sortition into government structures.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] The idea is that sortition could introduce a new dimension of representation and fairness in political systems, countering issues associated with electoral politics.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] This concept has garnered academic interest, with scholars exploring the potential of random selection in enhancing the democratic process, both in political frameworks and organizational structures.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] The ongoing study and debate surrounding the use of sortition reflect its enduring relevance and potential as a tool for political innovation and integrity.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Randomization is a core principle in statistical theory, whose importance was emphasized by Charles S.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Peirce in "Illustrations of the Logic of Science" (1877–1878) and "A Theory of Probable Inference" (1883).
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Its application in statistical methodologies is multifaceted and includes critical processes such as randomized controlled experiments, survey sampling and simulations.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] In the realm of scientific research, particularly within clinical study designs, constraints such as limited manpower, material resources, financial backing, and time necessitate a selective approach to participant inclusion.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Despite the broad spectrum of potential participants who fulfill the inclusion criteria, it is impractical to incorporate every eligible individual in the target population due to these constraints.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Therefore, a representative subset of treatment groups is chosen based on the specific requirements of the research.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] A randomized sampling method is employed to ensure the integrity and representativeness of the study.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] This method ensures that all qualified subjects within the target population have an equal opportunity to be selected.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Such a strategy is pivotal in mirroring the overall characteristics of the target population and in mitigating the risk of selection bias.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] The selected samples (or continuous non-randomly sampled samples) are grouped using randomization methods so that all research subjects in the sample have an equal chance of entering the experimental group or the control group and receiving corresponding treatment.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] In particular, the random grouping after the research subjects are stratified can make the known or unknown influencing factors between the groups basically consistent, thereby enhancing the comparability between the groups.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Survey sampling uses randomization, following the criticisms of previous "representative methods" by Jerzy Neyman in his 1922 report to the International Statistical Institute.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] It randomly displays the answer options to survey participants, which prevents order bias caused by the tendency of respondents to choose the first option when the same order is presented to different respondents.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] To overcome this, researchers can give the answer options in a random order so that the respondents allocate some time to read all the options and choose an honest answer.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] For example, consider an automobile dealer who wants to conduct a feedback survey and ask the respondents to select their preferred automobile brand.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] The user can create a study with randomized answers to display the different automobile brands so that the respondents do not see them in the same order.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Some important methods of statistical inference use resampling from the observed data.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Multiple alternative versions of the data-set that "might have been observed" are created by randomization of the original data-set, the only one observed.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] The variation of statistics calculated for these alternative data-sets is a guide to the uncertainty of statistics estimated from the original data.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] In many scientific and engineering fields, computer simulations of real phenomena are commonly used.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] When the real phenomena are affected by unpredictable processes, such as radio noise or day-to-day weather, these processes can be simulated using random or pseudo-random numbers.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] One of the most prominent uses of randomization in simulations is in Monte Carlo methods.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] These methods rely on repeated random sampling to obtain numerical results, typically to model probability distributions or to estimate uncertain quantities in a system.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Randomization also allows for the testing of models or algorithms against unexpected inputs or scenarios.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] This is essential in fields like machine learning and artificial intelligence, where algorithms must be robust against a variety of inputs and conditions.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Randomization plays a fascinating and often underappreciated role in literature, music, and art, where it introduces elements of unpredictability and spontaneity.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Pioneered by surrealists and later popularized by writers like William S.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Burroughs, automatic writing and cut-up techniques involve randomly rearranging text to create new literary forms.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] It disrupts linear narratives, fostering unexpected connections and meanings.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] In aleatoric music, elements of the composition are left to chance or the performer's discretion.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Composers like John Cage used randomization to create music where certain elements are unforeseeable, resulting in each performance being uniquely different.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Modern musicians sometimes employ computer algorithms that generate music based on random inputs.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] These compositions can range from electronic music to more classical forms, where randomness plays a key role in creating harmony, melody, or rhythm.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Some artists in abstract expressionism movement, like Jackson Pollock, used random methods (like dripping or splattering paint) to create their artworks.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] This approach emphasizes the physical act of painting and the role of chance in the artistic process.Also, contemporary artists often use algorithms and computer-generated randomness to create visual art.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] This can result in intricate patterns and designs that would be difficult or impossible to predict or replicate manually.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Although historically "manual" randomization techniques (such as shuffling cards, drawing pieces of paper from a bag, spinning a roulette wheel) were common, nowadays automated techniques are mostly used.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] As both selecting random samples and random permutations can be reduced to simply selecting random numbers, random number generation methods are now most commonly used, both hardware random number generators and pseudo-random number generators.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] Randomization is used in optimization to alleviate the computational burden associated to robust control techniques: a sample of values of the uncertainty parameters is randomly drawn and robustness is enforced for these values only.
[src:experimental-design/randomization] This approach has gained popularity by the introduction of rigorous theories that permit one to have control on the probabilistic level of robustness, see scenario optimization.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] In science, **randomized experiments** are the experiments that allow the greatest reliability and validity of statistical estimates of treatment effects.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] Randomization-based inference is especially important in experimental design and in survey sampling.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] In the statistical theory of design of experiments, randomization involves randomly allocating the experimental units across the treatment groups.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] For example, if an experiment compares a new drug against a standard drug, then the patients should be allocated to either the new drug or to the standard drug control using randomization.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] Randomized experimentation is *not* haphazard.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] Randomization reduces bias by equalising other factors that have not been explicitly accounted for in the experimental design (according to the law of large numbers).
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] Randomization also produces ignorable designs, which are valuable in model-based statistical inference, especially Bayesian or likelihood-based.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] In the design of experiments, the simplest design for comparing treatments is the "completely randomized design".
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] Some "restriction on randomization" can occur with blocking and experiments that have hard-to-change factors; additional restrictions on randomization can occur when a full randomization is infeasible or when it is desirable to reduce the variance of estimators of selected effects.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] Randomization of treatment in clinical trials pose ethical problems.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] In some cases, randomization reduces the therapeutic options for both physician and patient, and so randomization requires clinical equipoise regarding the treatments.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] Web sites can run randomized controlled experiments to create a feedback loop.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] A controlled experiment appears to have been suggested in the Old Testament's Book of Daniel.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] King Nebuchadnezzar proposed that some Israelites eat "a daily amount of food and wine from the king's table." Daniel preferred a vegetarian diet, but the official was concerned that the king would "see you looking worse than the other young men your age?
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] The king would then have my head because of you." Daniel then proposed the following controlled experiment: "Test your servants for ten days.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] Give us nothing but vegetables to eat and water to drink.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] Then compare our appearance with that of the young men who eat the royal food, and treat your servants in accordance with what you see".
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] Randomized experiments were institutionalized in psychology and education in the late eighteen-hundreds, following the invention of randomized experiments by C.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] Outside of psychology and education, randomized experiments were popularized by R.A.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] Fisher in his book *Statistical Methods for Research Workers*, which also introduced additional principles of experimental design.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] The Rubin Causal Model provides a common way to describe a randomized experiment.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] While the Rubin Causal Model provides a framework for defining the causal parameters (i.e., the effects of a randomized treatment on an outcome), the analysis of experiments can take a number of forms.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] The model assumes that there are two potential outcomes for each unit in the study: the outcome if the unit receives the treatment and the outcome if the unit does not receive the treatment.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] The difference between these two potential outcomes is known as the treatment effect, which is the causal effect of the treatment on the outcome.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] Most commonly, randomized experiments are analyzed using ANOVA, student's t-test, regression analysis, or a similar statistical test.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] The model also accounts for potential confounding factors, which are factors that could affect both the treatment and the outcome.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] By controlling for these confounding factors, the model helps to ensure that any observed treatment effect is truly causal and not simply the result of other factors that are correlated with both the treatment and the outcome.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] The Rubin Causal Model is a useful a framework for understanding how to estimate the causal effect of the treatment, even when there are confounding variables that may affect the outcome.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] This model specifies that the causal effect of the treatment is the difference in the outcomes that would have been observed for each individual if they had received the treatment and if they had not received the treatment.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] In practice, it is not possible to observe both potential outcomes for the same individual, so statistical methods are used to estimate the causal effect using data from the experiment.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] Empirically differences between randomized and non-randomized studies, and between adequately and inadequately randomized trials have been difficult to detect.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] Randomization is the cornerstone of many scientific claims.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] To randomize, means that we can eliminate the confounding factors.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] Say we study the effect of **A** on **B.** Yet, there are many unobservables **U** that potentially affect **B** and confound our estimate of the finding.
[src:experimental-design/randomized-experiment] To explain these kinds of issues, statisticians or econometricians nowadays use directed acyclic graph.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] In engineering, science, and statistics, **replication** is the process of repeating a study or experiment under the same or similar conditions.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] It is a crucial step to test the original claim and confirm or reject the accuracy of results as well as for identifying and correcting the flaws in the original experiment.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] ASTM, in standard E1847, defines replication as "... the repetition of the set of all the treatment combinations to be compared in an experiment.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] For a full factorial design, replicates are multiple experimental runs with the same factor levels.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] You can replicate combinations of factor levels, groups of factor level combinations, or even entire designs.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] For instance, consider a scenario with three factors, each having two levels, and an experiment that tests every possible combination of these levels (a full factorial design).
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] One complete replication of this design would comprise 8 runs ( $2^{3}$ ).
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] The design can be executed once or with several replicates.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] There are two main types of replication in statistics.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] First, there is a type called “exact replication” (also called "direct replication"), which involves repeating the study as closely as possible to the original to see whether the original results can be precisely reproduced.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] For instance, repeating a study on the effect of a specific diet on weight loss using the same diet plan and measurement methods.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] The second type of replication is called “conceptual replication.” This involves testing the same theory as the original study but with different conditions.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] For example, testing the same diet's effect on blood sugar levels instead of weight loss, using different measurement methods.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] Both exact (direct) replications and conceptual replications are important.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] Direct replications help confirm the accuracy of the findings within the conditions that were initially tested.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] On the hand conceptual replications examine the validity of the theory behind those findings and explore different conditions under which those findings remain true.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] In essence conceptual replication provides insights, into how generalizable the findings are.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] Replication is not the same as repeated measurements of the same item.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] Both repeat and replicate measurements involve multiple observations taken at the same levels of experimental factors.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] However, repeat measurements are collected during a single experimental session, while replicate measurements are gathered across different experimental sessions.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] Replication in statistics evaluates the consistency of experiment results across different trials to ensure external validity, while repetition measures precision and internal consistency within the same or similar experiments.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] Replicates Example: Testing a new drug's effect on blood pressure in separate groups on different days.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] Repeats Example: Measuring blood pressure multiple times in one group during a single session.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] In replication studies within the field of statistics, several key methods and concepts are employed to assess the reliability of research findings.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] P-Values: The p-value is a measure of the probability that the observed data would occur by chance if the null hypothesis were true.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] In replication studies p-values help us determine whether the findings can be consistently replicated.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] A low p-value in a replication study indicates that the results are not likely due to random chance.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] For example, if a study found a statistically significant effect of a test condition on an outcome, and the replication find statistically significant effects as well, this suggests that the original finding is likely reproducible.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] Confidence Intervals: Confidence intervals provide a range of values within which the true effect size is likely to fall.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] In replication studies, comparing the confidence intervals of the original study and the replication can indicate whether the results are consistent.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] For example, if the original study reports a treatment effect with a 95% confidence interval of [5, 10], and the replication study finds a similar effect with a confidence interval of [6, 11], this overlap indicates consistent findings across both studies.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] As an example, consider a continuous process which produces items.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] Batches of items are then processed or treated.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] Finally, tests or measurements are conducted.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] Several options might be available to obtain ten test values.
[src:experimental-design/replication-statistics] Each option would call for different data analysis methods and yield different conclusions.
